I laughed all the way through. A few points, though:

"Testing has shown that anyone who manages to escape a vehicle that he has been driving as it moves is still doomed to death" This is long and awkward, and followed by a semicolon. You might want to cut down this sentence and/or split the two, to keep the flow of the paragraph.
"Dr. Gerald himself, oddly enough, always survives whatever horrors he puts a vehicle through." This is just me being a grammar person, but it's 'whatever horrors through which he puts a vehicle'. Dangling participles are optional, though.
"throwing themselves in his path" I feel like this should be 'into his path'.


There are probably more, but I just woke up ten minutes ago and might end up over-nitpicking. Get with me on IRC if you want a full proofread. Again, hilarious article.







